###part a###

# Create a 2x2 contingency table of exacerbations by treatment group with 'Yes' first
exac_by_treatment_1 <- table(data$Exac, data$Treatment)
exac_by_treatment <- exac_by_treatment_1[c(2, 1), ] # swapping rows here so it can be used as required by epi.2by2 for OR and RR

# View the resulting contingency table
exac_by_treatment
##      
##       Active Placebo
##   Yes    128     158
##   No     133     109
# Calculate the proportion of patients with an exacerbation in each treatment group
prop_exac_placebo <- exac_by_treatment["Yes", "Placebo"] / sum(exac_by_treatment[, "Placebo"])
prop_exac_active <- exac_by_treatment["Yes", "Active"] / sum(exac_by_treatment[, "Active"])

# creating a table with both the values and proportion
table_percentages_exacerbation <- tbl_summary(data,
                              include = c(Exac), # which category to include
                              type = all_dichotomous() ~ "categorical", # !imp! changing variable type to categorical, otherwise only one level will show
                              statistic = list(
                                all_categorical() ~ "{n} ({p}%)"
                              ),
                              by = Treatment) # split table by group

###part b###

# Perform Chi-squared test
chisq_result <- chisq.test(exac_by_treatment) # selecting the chi-squared test since these are two independent unordered categorical variables that form a r x c contingency table
# H0: No difference in outcomes. i.e. no difference in proportion of patients that had exacerbation, at 12-month between the treatment and placebo groups 
# H1: There is a difference in outcomes. i.e. a difference in proportion of patients that had exacerbation, at 12-month between the treatment and placebo groups 

# Display the test result
chisq_result
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  exac_by_treatment
## X-squared = 5.059, df = 1, p-value = 0.0245
#check the expected cell counts
chisq_result$expected  
##      
##        Active Placebo
##   Yes 141.375 144.625
##   No  119.625 122.375
# all are greater than 5

# The p-value is 0.0245, 
# The results is statistically significant at 5% significance level.

###part c###

# Calculate RR, OR, and their confidence intervals
epi.2by2(exac_by_treatment, outcome = "as.rows") 
##              Exposed +    Exposed -      Total
## Outcome +          128          158        286
## Outcome -          133          109        242
## Total              261          267        528
## 
## Point estimates and 95% CIs:
## -------------------------------------------------------------------
## Inc risk ratio                                 0.83 (0.71, 0.97)
## Inc odds ratio                                 0.66 (0.47, 0.94)

## Fisher exact test that OR = 1: Pr>chi2 = 0.023
##  Wald confidence limits
##  CI: confidence interval
##  * Outcomes per 100 population units
# positive outcome is patients had an exacerbation at 12-month follow-up period
#The RR of having an exacerbation is 0.83 with 95% CI (0.71, 0.97). Patients on active treatment are 0.83 times less likely to have an exacerbation compared to placebo. The 95% CI does not include 1 which suggests that we reject the null hypothesis that the risk of having an exacerbation in the two groups is the same at 5% significance level. 
#The OR of having an exacerbation is 0.66 with 95% CI (0.47, 0.94). The odds of having an exacerbation for patients on placebo are 0.66 times less compared to placebo. The 95% CI does not include 1 which suggests that we reject the null hypothesis that the odds of having an exacerbation in the two groups is the same at 5% significance level. 

###part d###

# Calculate Absolute Risk Difference (ARD)
ARD <- round(prop_exac_active - prop_exac_placebo,2)
# calculated in part a, ARD = Risk in Active Group - Risk in Placebo Group, Where Risk = Proportion of exacerbations in each group.
# this can also be obtained directly from the RR/OR output (Attrib risk in the exposed *)

# Calculate Number Needed to Treat (NNT)
NNT <- round(1 / abs(ARD),0)

# Calculate standard error for ARD
n_placebo <- sum(exac_by_treatment[, "Placebo"])
n_active <- sum(exac_by_treatment[, "Active"])
SE_ARD <- sqrt((prop_exac_placebo * (1 - prop_exac_placebo)) / n_placebo + (prop_exac_active * (1 - prop_exac_active)) / n_active)

# Calculate 95% confidence interval for ARD
CI_ARD <- round(ARD + c(-1, 1) * 1.96 * SE_ARD,2)
# this can also be obtained directly from the RR/OR output (Attrib risk in the exposed *)

# Output the results
ARD

CI_ARD
## [1] -0.18 -0.02
NNT

###part c###
# Perform likelihood ratio test to compare 'model' and 'model_severity'
lr_test <- anova(model, model_severity, test = "Chisq")

# View the likelihood ratio test results
lr_test
## Analysis of Deviance Table
## 
## Model 1: Exac ~ Treatment + Age + Sex + Centre
## Model 2: Exac ~ Treatment + Age + Sex + Centre + Asthsev
##   Resid. Df Resid. Dev Df Deviance Pr(>Chi)
## 1       520     708.92                     
## 2       519     708.55  1  0.36996    0.543
#the LRT result (Pr(>Chi) = 0.543) indicates that the addition of the 'Asthsev' variable did not significantly improve the model's fit.
#Thus, the first model without 'Asthsev' (severity of asthma at baseline) is selected as the chosen model

###part b###

# checking homogeneity of variance
sd(data_active$Totex)/sd(data_placebo$Totex)
## [1] 0.8108684
# confirming homogeneity of variance (less than twice), proceed with t-test

# perform t test (parametric test)
t.test(data_active$Totex, data_placebo$Totex, var.equal=T)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data_active$Totex and data_placebo$Totex
## t = -2.3087, df = 526, p-value = 0.02134
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.69584581 -0.05605913
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  1.103448  1.479401
# for parametric test, running the two sample t-test as the data are not paired. 
# the data are not normally distributed but the sample size is large enough the t-test would be robust (>30)
# null hypothesis is true difference in mean equals to 0
# p-value = 0.021, thus we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis

# Perform Wilcoxon-Mann-Whitney U test (non-parametric test) 
wilcox.test(data_active$Totex, data_placebo$Totex)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  data_active$Totex and data_placebo$Totex
## W = 31008, p-value = 0.02023
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
# for non-parametric test, running the Wilcoxon-Mann-Whitney U test as the data are not paired. 
# null hypothesis is true location shift is equal to 0
# p-value = 0.020, thus we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis
